column168: Upon transferring a van load of hazardous waste from Veolia’s intransit transfer facility located in Port Arthur, TX to the TSDF also located in Port Arthur, TX, the driver identified a small drip from the front portion of the van.  The drip was contained and the van trailer was moved directly to the unloading dock at the disposal facility.  The trailer was off-loaded and the leaking container was identified.  The drum was a 55 gallon DM and appeared to have two pinholes toward the bottom on one side of the drum.  The drum was overpacked for disposal and the van trailer was decontaminated.

column168: Loader was doing second half of a split load when the pump started making a strange sound. He immediately shut down the pump and went to close the railcar valve. He secured the valve handle in what he thought was the closed position. He then went to open the filter housing to check the filter screen because the strange sound the pump was making had previously been found to be caused by debris being caught in the filter screen. When he opened the housing lid, ethanol began flowing out of the filter housing. The yard foreman happened to be coming by the transfer site at this time and observed the situation. He immediately went and moved the valve handle to the opposite position which closed the railcar valve. The ethanol stopped flowing in approx. 15 seconds. There was approx. 25 gallons of ethanol released onto the pavement. The ethanol was immediately contained on the asphalt without any reaching any storm drains or other ground sources. The product was cleaned up and the materials disposed of in a labeled container.
column169: 1. Immediately retrain all loaders and yard personnel on properly closing railcar valves. This training will include the different valves associated with different railcar types.   2. Require verification that railcar valves are closed and hoses are properly connected prior to performing any maintenance on a product pump.

column168: During routine unloading process, Employee connected transfer hose to IBC outlet valve and proceeded making additional hose connections in preparation for product transfer. Before transfer operation began, Employee heard hose fall from tote and product immediately began flowing from damaged valve. Employee attempted to reposition valve handle to stop leak however; valve seat had been damaged with failure. Employee and customer quickly assembled draw tube pipe to allow contents to be pumped from container vent cap to mitigate release. Exact release amount is unknown due to limited receiving tank calculations prior to delivery. Estimated release is between 50-70 fluid gallons. Environmental cleanup contractor (Mid-America)was contacted to coordinate cleanup and remediation of affected areas.
column169: Review of valve area suggests unit was defective in some manner likely during the molding process of the flanged valve. Valve does not exhibit signs of abuse, wear or damage that would have contributed to this incident. Incident was not contributed to inadequate training and recommendations are limited to enhanced inspection and testing of external components assembled during container manufacture.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While in the facility yard, free product was discovered leaking from a trailer.  SET Environmental, Inc. of Bridgeview, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  SET Environmental, Inc. investigated the trailer, and discovered two (2) leaking 330-gallon metal totes.  A combined total of approximately 10 gallons released from the two leaking totes.  Apparently the release was a result of faulty valves on the totes.  SET Environmental, Inc. applied absorbent material as needed and proceeded to transfer the product from the leaking totes into twelve (12) 55-gallon recovery drums.  The twelve (12) 55-gallon drums of product and the two empty totes were left on site pending shipper instructions.  One (1) 55-gallon drum of contaminated absorbent material was transported by SET Environmental, Inc. to their facility in Bridgeview, Illinois pending disposal coordination.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During a routine inspection at the Ceciltown Weigh and Inspection Station in Warwick, Maryland, a release was discovered from the Slay Transportation Co., Inc. vehicle.  Apparently, less than one gallon of benzyl chloride escaped from a faulty gasket on the manway cover of the tank truck.  The free product was contained within the porthole at the top of the tank, and did not impact the environment or threaten any waters of the state.  The Cecil County Emergency Services Hazmat Team was on site during inspection, and Slay Transportation Co., Inc. representatives responded to replace the loose gasket, and secure shipment, prior to proceeding.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a faulty gasket on the vehicle, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel, and perform routine maintenance on all equipment.

column168: During unloading procedures, the pump on the unit failed and released approximately 20 gallons of the material onto the cement area.  There were no storm drains, surface waters, or soils impacted during this incident.  ERTS then dispatched a contractor to the site to provide initial response and cleanup activities.  The material was diluted and containerized with absorbents into 2-55 gallon drums.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  During a routine inspection at the Triple Crown Services' rail yard in Granite City, Illinois, a leak was discovered inside the trailer.  Apparently, one (1) 350 gallon tote, had a cracked weld on the seam of the tote, which resulted in the release of approximately 15 gallons of free product.  Bellon Environmental Company of Saint Louis, Missouri was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, free product was detected along the asphalt surface and on the trailer floor.  Bellon Environmental Company applied floor dry to the asphalt surface and trailer floor to recover the free product.  The spent floor dry was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum, pending disposal.  Bellon Environmental Company proceeded to transfer the remaining product from the damaged tote into seven (7) 55 gallon drums. (6 full, 1 partial)  The virgin product and damaged tote were left at the TCS yard, pending disposition from the shipper.  One (1) 55-gallon drum of spent floor dry was transported off site, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a cracked weld, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: While loading it appears from the damage to the container that the forklift caused damage to the seam of the tote tank causing the leak. Consignee contained the spilled and handled the clean up and any disposal assoicated with the spill.

During unloading procedures it was found that 14 pails of the material on pallets had a faulty lid seal.  ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site to place the damaged containers into overpack drums and left them at the facility for the shipper (PPG) to collect for disposal activities.

A vacuum trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was dispatched to a shipper’s location to load a shipment of material for disposal.  During the loading operation, the equipment operator became distracted and failed to cease pumping operations when the tank reached the maximum loading volume.  This resulted in the loss of vacuum to the unit which allowed approximately 40 gallons to overflow out of the top fill hole.  The equipment operator immediately shut down the loading operation and initiated the clean up of the loading area.  All spill debris was containerized and was placed into storage pending off-site disposal.  In addition, the tank was cleaned and all residues were removed from the exterior surface of the tank.  Please note that an inspection of the vehicle indicated that the tank was in working order and the cause was directly attributed to operator error.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver of the unit in question has been re-instructed on the attendance requirements when loading or unloading a cargo tank and the absolute necessity to be in direct control of the loading operation at all times.  Furthermore, the driver has been advised that future incidents involving lack of attention will result in appropriate disciplinary action and retraining requirements.

column168: Approximately 7 pallets of material (3,724 Ibs) self-ignited while in temporary storage during the course of transportation. The shipper utilized the ORM-D classification in offering the material for transport and fully disclosed all known hazards of this material. This material was a recalled consumer product to be utilized as a treatment chemical at PSC’s TSDF in Fernley NV. The MSDS for this material was reviewed to initially determine the classification and handling of this material. PSC decided to take further precautionary measures by temporarily storing the material in a covered isolated area. After storage for approx 4 months at the PSC-Nortru Transfer Facility (Detroit) the material was relocated to another isolated area of the facility in preparation for final shipment to Fernley NV. The material ignited approx. 4 hours after it was relocated on 08.01.2008. It was noted that the material was exposed to direct sunlight on this day. A CPSC advisory released on April 03, 2008 fully disclosed the nature of this recalled product and its potential instability. 911 was called for response action. The fire was observed from a safe distance while portable fire extinguishers were on standby to minimize the risk of spreading. The fire department remained off-site and diverted traffic away from the facility entrance on Freud St. When the fire subsided (approx 45 minutes), employees doused the area with water to completely extinguish the flame and cool the residue pile (consumed material + pallets + packaging). Clean-up activities will include fire residue removal, fire fighting water removal and decontamination of the concrete containment area. No one experienced any ill health effects. 6 drums of waste residue and 7,500 gal. of fire fighting/decon water were generated and removed from the site.

column168: At approximately 1030 on 8/14/2008, Nuway Environmental Services LLC pulled into the Univar Charlotte facility with a shipment from the Univar Spartanburg facility.   Upon arrival the trailer was leaking product from the rear door.  After reviewing the drivers paperwork it was determined that the only liquid material on the vehicle was Hydorgen Peroxide 35%.  The truck was pulled into containment and on-site response personnel entered the trailer and identified the leaking tote.  The tote was removed from the trailer and the remaining material transferred to another tote.  The trailer was unloaded and flushed three times with water to dilute the spilled H2O2.  The flush water was captured on the containment pad and large amounts of water was used to dilute the containment area prior to pumping off the material for disposal.  An estimated 516 liquid pounds of materail was lost with most all of it being contained in the trailer and a minimal amount being leaked out.
column169: A more frequent visible and testing inspection of containers of this type could possibly identify potential container failure risk of this type prior to it occuring.  In addition, drivers have been instructed to perform more frequent inspections during transport so as to possibly identify such leaks more quickly.  The maintaining of spill response and containment supplies on trailers transporting hazardous materials can help minmize and mitigate any leaks or spills during transport.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste made a routine stop during transportation for the purpose of consolidating two less than truckload quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation.  During the transfer operation, the fork-lift operator was moving a pallet that broke allowing the non-bulk package to fall off the pallet dislodging the lid.  The contents of the container was released to the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel immedialty ceased transfer operations and recontainerized the waste and decontaminated the floor of the trailer.  all material, including the spill debris was then placed back into transit and disposed of at the intended waste management facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the loading personnel have been reinstructed that before a pallet is moved, it is inspected for damage and propoer loading.  If a damaged loading device is discovered, facility personnel have been instructed to replace damaged devices and repace before attempting to reposition the device and its contents.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to NYK Line as non-hazardous cargo by Hapag-Lloyd, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the NYK Line container vessel NYK Daedalus V. 06W33 from New York, New York to Cebu, Phillipines.    Hapag-Lloyd advised NYK Line after the vessel had sailed from New York of the following hazardous materials in the container that was not originally  booked or otherwise identified:    -  UN1044 FIRE EXTINGUISHERS, CL 2.2 (12 CYLINDERS)  -  UN1002 AIR, COMPRESSED, CL 2.2  (24 CYLINDERS)    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the hazardous material, and the  container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the hazardous item.    Hapag-Lloyd subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to NYK Line.

column168: At consignee, the driver supplies the product transfer hoses. The consignees' operator helps the driver hook the hoses to the consignees' pump. the driver had all the necessary paperwork signed and was given permision to open the trailer product valves. The operator started his pump and within several seconds after the pump started to mpve product the hose on the pressure side of the pumpe failed. The hose parted from the hose coupling resulting in the spill. The driver shut the trailer valves and the pump was shut down. spill was contained and cleaned up by the consignee. the consignee is still investigating this but early reports indicate that there may have been a blockage in the receiving line (piping).
column169: To early to say, the consignee is still investigating this incident I will update.  As far as the driver. All he dose is supply the hoses which were new and operate the trailer valves.  The consigne operates the pump.

column168: On August 11, 2008 at 16:16, personnel in the CSXT rail yard in Hamlet, NC, discovered DAX 7074, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC,  Report # 2008-08-11-00141. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the top operated bottom outlet plug valve was open slightly; the 2 inch auxiliary ball valve was open and the valve plug was not installed. Contractor personnel closed the valves, installed the valve plug and neutralized the product released onto the ballast.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code:  610  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column168: REPORT 1  8/1/08: At approximately 11:30AM, CR Risk Mgmt. A. Richter received call from CR Trainmaster C. Farina, advising CR crew detected an ammonia odor from tank car GATX 944, residue last contained Ammonia Solutions.    REACT activated by Mr. Richter.  Upon arrival, Mr. Richter met with CR mechanical inspector and Mr. J. McHugh, Tyburn RR (TYRR), Morrisville, PA, from where the car had been shipped (unloaded on a track at TYRR by Tanner Industries).  Inspection of car found slight ammonia odor eminating from the top of the car.  Further inspection by both Mr. Richter and REACT's R. Gould, found 83ppm reading from the vacuum relief valve located underneath the bread box. It was suspected that the internal pressure had built up during the day (non-insulated tank car) causing the detection of the product.    Due the nature of the product and intermitent odors detected, it was determined that the car would be moved back into the Tyburn RR facility, from which it originated, so that a contractor called in by the car owner/lessee could make the necessary repairs in a more controlled environment.  Car was moved back into Tyburn Railroad facility at approximately 0300, 8/2/08, without further incident and detection of odor.    Emergency response contractor SPSI (qualified and registered Class F/G) inspected the car at the Tyburn facility that day, and found the odor originating from the vacuum relief valve.  The vacuum relief was removed and replaced with a solid 2.5" solid threaded plug. While pressure testing to insure leakproofness, another vapor leak was found at the 3" liquid valve where it is threaded into the "male mounting nipple" (as reported by SPSI).  Attempts to secure the valve were unsuccessful.    Car owner/lessee Terra International applied for, and received FRA Movement Approval (08080252) to have the car shipped from Tyburn Railroad, to GATX Rail Corp., Waycross, GA for inspection and repair. CODE: 200  NARRI: 5(5+3+0)x(2+0)=80    *Loose Manway Bolts
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: A BNSF switch crew in the railyard reported PTLX 223945 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) had leaked with product sheen on its side shell. PTLX 223945 was cordoned off and nearby rail operations were suspended. BNSF mechanical and contract responder's initial investigation revealed that the 20 inch manway gasket was torn with a portion of the gasket material missing. A new manway gasket was installed and the manway was resecured on 8/08/08 and rail operations resumed. Spillage on PTLX 223945 was wiped and no ground impact was evident.  On 8/09/08, the same contractor returned after PTLX 223945 was reported venting in the railyard. Responders reinspected PTLX 223945 in greater detail and found several fitness and securement deficiencies. The vacuum relief valve (VRV) was not functioning properly. The VRV was removed and its orifice plugged. The threaded liquid valve was found to be less than tool tight. The valve was removed, Teflon tape applied to its threads, reinstalled and properly tool tightened. The liquid valve's mounting flange bolt nuts were found to be less than tool tight and all four of these nuts were tool tightened. In addition, the responders found the one inch vapor line closure plug at its threaded connection atop the housing plate to be less than tool tight. Responders determined that this was the source of the vapor release. The plug was removed and responders noted that the threads in the orifice appeared slightly worn. Teflon tape was applied to the plug's threads, the plug reinstalled and tool tightened. No further reports of venting were reported after the securement of PTLX 223945 was completed on 8/09/08. PTLX 223945 was moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting RESCAR mobile repair service that was notified to inspect and pressure test PTLX 223945, correcting any/all deficiencies discovered prior to releasing PTLX 223945.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: BNSF mechanical personnel reported GATX 44734 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard leaking product from the manway area onto its side shell. A nearby BNSF contractor was called and immediately inspected GATX 44734. The contractor observed product being expelled from between the manway lid and the manway nozzle. The contractor relieved internal pressure from within GATX 44734 and opened the secured manway lid. Contractor reported that the manway gasket was missing and the product was approximately 1 1/2 inches from the manway lip (an overload condition). A new manway gasket was installed and the manway lid was resecured. GATX 44734 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. No further product expulsion was observed after the manway was secured. All spillage was rapidly evaporating and no ground impact was evident. The shipper was notified to arrange for product reduction from GATX 44734 to achieve a suitable product outage level. On 8/22/08, 3000 gallons of product from GATX 44734 was off-loaded into a shipper arranged tanker truck. This was accomplished by 1500 hrs. CDT, 8/22/08 without further incident. New seals numbered 2877031 and 2877023 were applied to the top and bottom appurtenances respectively.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings, including adherence to the appropriate product outages for the expected ambient temperatures.

UTLX 210036 was noted by carrier personnel with product on top of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL, responded and found the liquid valve operating handle open one-quarter turn and the valve plug finger tight.The valve was properly closed and the plug made tool tight stopping the release.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: This car was observed leaking during switching operations.  The car was isolated.  Upon closer inspection, the pipe between the pressure plate and the vapor valve was broken.  The vapor valve was being held on top of the railcar by a chain.  The valve was removed and a temporary plug / patch stopped the leak.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: U/A the IBC was noticed leaking in the carriers trailer. Due to the heavy odor a contractor was called to clean up the leak. Further investigation by the contractor revealed the IBC had a stress crack in the top of the container approximately 2.5 inches and was located on the seam of the IBC. This is where the product spilled from the container as the liquid sloshed during transportation. The contractor cleaned up a minimal amount of released material as the product had mostly evaporated and took the waste materials with them for disposal. The tote was moved on to the consignee and delivered clear. No further actions are necessary at this time.
column169: Thorough inspection of containers prior to loading may have caught the defect in the tote. Perhaps a mandatory pressure test on such containers with a resonable frequency would reveal defective containers.

column168: UTLX 207202 was noted by carrier personnel with product on top of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, responded and tightened 2 of 8 manway cover bolts stopping the release.  The loose bolts were the 2 closest to the manway cover hinge and were only finger tight.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The carton was noticed to be leaking U/A to the terminal. Further investigation revealed the top corner was crushed and the inner can was crushed at the handle. column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 2847 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) emanating a vapor 'mist' along with a product odor during movement in the railyard. GATX 2847 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. The initial inspection of GATX 2847 by BNSF contract responders resulted in no obvious leak source discovered. GATX 2847 was then moved within the isolation area while being observed by the contract responders. Movement was stopped and responders concluded that the liquid and vapor closure plugs were not fully sealing. The plugs were removed, the threaded areas cleaned and then Teflon taped. The plugs were then reinstalled and tool tightened. No further product release (mist or odor) was noted during subsequent movements of GATX 2847 in the railyard. Response was concluded by 1000 hrs. CDT, 8/04/08. Any product release evaporated and no ground impact from any release or spillage was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver had finished transferring product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  When he disconnected his hose, the product siphoned back out of the tank.  It went on the concrete and into a sand pit.  It was in danger of overflowing the sand pit and into the city sewer.  A response vendor was called out with a vac truck to clean up the spill.  The driver did get some product on his arm and leg, took a 15-minute shower and was transferred to the hospital to be checked out.  He was examined and released back to work.  The driver had been wearing gloves, hardhat, face shield, safety glasses, long sleeves and long pants.  He was not wearing his prescribed chemical suit.
column169: The storage tank should have had a check valve on it to prevent product from being siphoned out.  driver's employment has been terminated for not following proper procedure.

column168: Driver used product pump to unload 1006 gallons of product into a 1500 gallon storage tank located in a building.  Storage tank had 290 gallons in it before the delivery.  That should have left a 200 gallon headroom.  He used a short burst of air (5 psi) to clear 40' of hose.  As he did that, product came out of top vent on tank. The customer hosed it to their system.
column169: Storage tank had a sight glass but the readings had to be coverted to actual gallons and the driver did not have the conversion numbers.  Customer had provided the beginning reading to the driver.  An easier to read sight gauge would have helped. There may have been more product in the tank than registered.  Also, maybe less pressure to clear the line or close the valve more.

column168: CN mechanical department employee noted a small amount product dripping from the bottom outlet valve of tank car ULTX 67924(L / ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES, N.O.S.) during an inbound train inspection at the CN Champaign Yard, Urbana, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the bottom outlet valve handle retaining nut was loose allowing a small amount of product to escape. Retaining nut secured, tank car released for movement.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Our Employee was filling the tank- filled to 75% and also the fixed liquid gage (dip tube) went down at the 80% mark.  The EE disconnected from the tank, and about 5 min later…. - after EE walked away, filled out paperwork, and rolled up his hose- he heard the relief valve start spewing propane vapor.   We know the tank was not overfilled.  Sometimes the spring in the pressure relief valve will give out or become loose and release pressure with out re-seating.  Nothing could be done to stop the release.
column169: Our Employee made sure no one from the camp was in nearby buildings then called the Fire Department. The Fire Department responded and remained on site spraying the propane vapor until the release is complete.  Our Employee also stayed on site until the release is complete.  This is a customer owned tank which means Ferrellgas was not in possession of the propane at the time of the incident.  Also, the release did no occur during transportation, including loading, unloading or temporary storage related to transportation.

column168: Driver had transferred the product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He was using 5 sections of transfer hose. He let the product skim down the inside of the cargo tank and then opened the discharge valve 1/2 turn to walk the hose up hill to empty product out of the hose.  When he was 4 sections of hose away, the customer fitting on the fill line snapped off and product sprayed out of the hose. The customer hosed the spilled product to their system.
column169: The fill line connection was 1 1/2 feet off the ground and the brace for the hose was not too sturdy.  The customer will install a better brace for the hose to take the weight off of the fitting.

column168: The driver had just started the transfer of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank using 3 sections of transfer hose and his pump.  The middle section of hose developed a pinhole leak and started to spray product.  The driver shut down and replaced the section of hose.  He wiped up with spill pads.  A plant operator got some product on his clothes and immediately went to change and shower.  No adverse effects.
column169: We continue to routinely pressure check our hoses to check for problems.

column168: While draining the hose into a tank, the hose slipped out of the drivers gloved hand, came off the fitting, and fell to the ground releasing 3 gallons.
column169: Safety flash was created and forwarded to all terminals, reinforcing the following lessons learned:    When handling the hose, make sure the driver is in the proper position, while lifting and/or rolling all contents of the hose into the storage tank.    Make sure gloves are clean, and free of any substance that may cause the hose to slip out of the driver's hands.    While handling, or draining the hose, maintain a tight grip, and make sure driver has complete control of the hose.    Drivers are to keep the hose connected while draining/rolling the hose.

column14: W of Hwy 441 on E Hwy 595
column168: Our commercial motor vehicle broke down on Highway 595. JJ Towing, out of Margate, FL was dispatched to tow our vehicle back to our yard. While towing the vehicle, some part on our truck overheated which caused a fire. No hazardous material was released during this incident and the fire was extinguished by the fire department. We are currently investigating if JJ Towing caged the brakes on our truck during the towing operation. It is suspected that this was not completed by JJ Towing. If the brakes were not caged, we suspect the air in the braking system blead out causing the parking brake to engage which may have resulted in the brakes and tires overheating causing the fire.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: Driver arrived on site to unload shipment.  He was directed to unloading area.  Driver had been to the location many times  Driver changed out the gasket on the Interchem hose prior to use.  Driver attached 2 sections of hose together (both Interchem Trucking & customer hose) to the back end of tanker to unload.  The Interchem hose was attached to the tanker and the customers hose was attached to the holding tank on site.  The 2 hoses were joined in the middle.  Driver began to pressurize the tanker with air from his tractor and a sample was removed for testing by the customer from the bleed off valve located on the tanker located before the hose conncetions on the tanker.  The driver already had on his ppe to attach the hoses and obtain the sample.  The driver proceeded to open the internal and external valves on the tanker to begin the unloading process.  By this time approximately 15 psi had been generated for internal pressure inside the tanker.  The driver went to the end of the tanker to check on the unloading after approximately 170 gallons had already been transferred.  As the driver bent down to check the connection at the back of the tanker, the hose ruptured 7-8 inches from the connection.  The acid sprayed the driver and the surrounding area.  The driver began to call for help as he walked down the tanker to shut off the engine to hault the air pressure from increasing inside the tanker.  The driver then entered a nearby safety shower to decontaminate himself.  By this time 514 gallons of acid had been lost to the unloading area through a break in the hose which covered 1/2- 2/3 the diameter of the hose.  The unloading area is cement lined and designed to control and contain any releases.  The acid dissolved the interal valve hydraulic pump line causing the release of the hydraulic fluid which in turn caused the internal valve to close.  The driver shutting off the air pressure and the internal valve closing is what limtied the release to 514 gallons.  By this time the customer had actived the EMS and the fire department arrived on site to treat the driver.  Once Interchem Trucking was notified of the incident, the National Response Center was notified.  This notification brought the MA DEP and the Coast Guard to the site as well as OSHA.  The customer's response team contained and cleaned up the spill.  The tractor and trailer were removed from the area and the driver was tacken to a local hospital before being transferred to a region hospital located in Rhode Island for treatment of chemcial burns.
column169: Drives have been retrained on the use of personal protective equipment.  Hoses to be replaced yearly, inspected every 6 months.  Drivers ppe use checked and new equipment has been issued to all drivers.  Incident reporting reviewd with all drivers.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: Driver was in the process of unloading. Part way into the unloading process hose started to leak through a cut of about 1 inch in length. Driver was in attendance and immediately shut off internal valve stopping flow of product. Spill occurred in a containment area and product did not extend beyond the containment area. Another hose was secured and delivery completed without incident.
column169: Supply better training for inspecting hoses prior to loading or unloading.

column168: AS THE DRUM WAS BEING LOADED ONTO A SHUTTLE VEHICLE A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED EMINATING FROM THE DRUM. THE DRUM REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE BAG & SALVAGE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS OPENED TO REVEAL NINE GLASS BOTTLES, AT LEAST THREE OF WHICH HAD CRACKED AND LEAKED THE BULK OF THEIR CONTENTS. THE BOTTLES WERE SURROUNDED BY STYROFOAM PEANUTS. NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS READILY OBSERVED. WHILE THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT OF THEIR PRIMARY RECEPTICLES, A BARRIER BAG PREVENTED THE LIQUID FROM COMPROMISING THE INTEGRITY OF THE FIBRE DRUM. DUE TO A LACK OF POSITIVE CLOSURE ON THE SCREW-ON CAPS OF THE GLASS JARS, THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED. I SPOKE TO SA CATHERINE ZAMPARELLI. THE FREIGHT IS ON A TEMPORARY HOLD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION. I HAVE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, JAMES SUPINSKI AND REQUESTED A COPY OF THE PACKAGING TEST REPORT.
column169: NO COMMENT PROVIDED

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: Pails were readied for shipping on 3 pallets by the shipper. Pails were shrink wrapped to the pallet. When plced on the pallet the handle boss on one pail was not placed correctly to keep it from rubbing the pail along side of it. Pallets were placed on a 28 foot tractor traiIe combination and shipped to destination. In transit, the handle boss rubbed a hole in the pail along side of it wearing a small hole in the pail about 1 inch from the tol of the pail allowing about 5 ounces of liquid to leak from the hole. DSR notified Larry McGillvray ( myself) at time of discovery. The leaking product was on the rear o the trailer, the first pallet to be unloaded. The spill was noticed when the trailer was opened therefore there was no equipment involved. I cleared the area of all erqployees, found the proper paper work to identify the leaking product, and found it to be hazardous material. At this time I notified all employees to stay away from affected area and notified Conway Safety department for proper instruction on how to handle the situation. Was told to use proper PPE and place leaking pail in prope OS&D area at the Butte Service Center. Placing all soiled floor dry that was used to soak up the spill also in the same container and label with the coso for identi ication. Notified OS&D personell with proper instruction to notify shipper for disposition.
column169: Proper spacing and handle boss placement of the pails would keep this from happening.

column168: ADMX 29685 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) staged and awaiting delivery to the consignee, was reported by a passing train crew that it was dripping product from the tank's bottom area. BNSF mechanical responders found product droplets emanating from the B-end bottom shell at or near the weld where the brake support bracket is attached to the outer shell. A receptacle was placed under ADMX 29685 and a temporary adhesive patch was applied over the leak source which stopped the product drips. The product within ADMX 29685 was transferred to another suitable tank car. Transfer was completed on 8/13/08 without further incident. All spillage evaporated. ADMX 29685 was earmarked to be directed to a qualified repair facility for root cause failure analysis and appropriate repairs.

column168: Driver did not report the spill at the time of the incident. A stain on the asphalt was noticed and other drivers reported the stain and an investigation was started. Video evidence pinned down the time of the spill. Driver at first did not cooperate with answering questions but later explained that the spill had occured when he opened his fill caps on the headers. The butterfly valve (the next valve after the internal valve) may not have been closed as required. Gasoline collected beyond the butterfly valve and escaped the pipe when the fill cap was removed. Driver cleaned spill with spill pads and washed down (against policy).
column169: Driver had just recently been trained on how to handle a spill including reporting all spills. Driver did not report the spill nor gave correct responses when questioned about his delivery to this sight. Driver resigned from the company.

The bulk material handler prepared the tankwagon for loading.  During the preparation there was some confusion about how to properly vent the tankwagon, a newer type, during loading.  This issue was resolved and the loading was initiated.  When loading comenced it was noticed the loading hose had not been coupled to the tankwagon causing the liquid material to spill out on the ground and tankwagon.  The flow was shutoff and 400 gallons were determined to have been spilled.  The material freezes below 84 deg C and became solid on the ground and tankwagon.  All the material was confined to the tankwagon loading area with no release outside the containment area.  The spill was cleaned up thoroughly and disposed of in non-hazardous waste drums.  Water run-off from steam cleaning was contained and processed by the on-site waste water treatment facility.  The tankwagon was also thoroughly cleaned before being released back to the carrier.
column169: The loading SOP was found to be lacking in detail as to the exact procedure to be used in loading.  Better wording would not have prevented the incident but it would have reduced the response time.  The wording will be changed.    Local controls at the point of loading could also have mitigated the size of the spill and will be considered for installation as a corrective action.    Positive contact verification via the DCS system could have prevented the incident by not allowing the load sequence to start without the hose being properly conected to the tankwagon.  This too is being considered as a corrective action.

column168: A BNSF track maintenance crew reported a product odor emanating from standing railcars in a yard track. Several tank cars containing Methyl Acrylate were inspected by BNSF contract responders to determine the odor source. Inspection of GLNX 2557 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) revealed a slight product staining around the manway nozzle. The results of the detailed inspection of the manway revealed that all manway securement bolts were tool tight but the manway gasket was missing. The responders applied a new manway gasket and resecured the manway cover. Seals numbered 267743 and 267741 that were removed from the manway and valve housing cover were replaced with seals numbered 00031690 and 00031683. The staining around the manway nozzle was wiped. Afterwards, no further product odor was evident.     GLNX 2557's side specification stencil indicated that the Tank Qualification was completed in 2000 and next due in 2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The terminal contacted the ABF Safety hotline reporting a strong smell of ammonia in a trailer containing 18 cylinders of Ammonia Anhydrous which was shipped as a 2.2 domestically but the special provisions require the shipping paper to list the product as an Inhalation Hazard. Upon receipt of the c  all, I gave instructions to pull the trailer away from the dock and into an isolated area on the yard. I then contacted the emergency phone number to Airgas which ultimately linked me to Chemtrec. I reported the incident and received a call back from an Airgas responder. Airgas assembled a team of 6   and responded to the incident. ABF could not and obviously would not get close enough to the cylinders to get package identification markings so we do not have that information for this report. In a follow-up call with the Airgas response team, they reported to me that one of the cylinders had the   neck improperly attached resulting in the cylinder leaking. The spilled amount listed on this report is a guess. Airgas stated they would have to monitor the cylinder to determine how much leaked, we have not been given any information at this time.

column168: Driver was using pump to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He was having problems with getting the product to move through his pump so he hooked air pressure up to it to help clear the blockage.  He failed to close the discharge valve on the trailer and the air pressure went back into the trailer instead of towards the storage tank.  About 1 gallon of product bubbled out of the manhole on the trailer on to the asphalt.  It was thinned with solvent and then cleaned up.
column169: This scenario does not happen too often but the driver will receive additional training on the proper procedure when using air pressure to clear a blockage on the pump.

column168: Driver was using his pump to transfer 736 gallons of product from the cargo tank to a 1030 gallon storage tank that had 242 gallons in it to start.  The storage tank was outside but the sight gauge for it was in a little room on the other side of the tank.  A plant operator was watching the gauge but by time he came out to notify the driver that it was full, the tank had overflowed.  There was still approximately 93 gallons of product in the cargo tank and the tranfer hose was also full.  According to the calculations, all the product should have fit.  Not sure if more was shipped than listed on the bill of lading or the sight gauge malfunctioned.
column169: There should have been better communication between the driver and the plant operator.  Plant operator should have alerted the driver sooner that is was almost full.

column168: A BNSF mechanical foreman reported product odor emanating from CRPX 9637 (DOT 112J400W tank car) while it was in queue for draft gear repair work at the BNSF yard repair track. Immediate inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders revealed that ice was forming on one of the liquid valves. This liquid valve was in the closed position, but its closure plug was found to be 3/4 turn less than tool tight. This loose closure plug was tool tightened by 1400 hrs. MDT, 8/28/08 and no further product odor was evident.  The specification stencil on the side of CRPX 9637 indicated that the tank qualification was completed in the year 2006 and next due in 2016.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: DBUX 301648 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard. DBUX 301648 was then carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. A BNSF contract responder immediately inspected DBUX 301648 finding 7 of 8 manway securement bolts less than tool tight and the manway gasket misaligned. The responder repositioned the manway gasket and properly secured the manway cover by tool tightening all securement bolts. Spillage that didn't evaporate on the tank shell was wiped and no ground impact from spillage was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: A BNSF track maintenance crew reported to the BNSF train dispatcher that during inspection of a passing BNSF train that they observed an entrained tank car that was leaking. The BNSF train crew was notified. The train was stopped and the train crew setout CITX 220093 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) on an industry track at Brantford, ND. BNSF and contract responders were summoned to inspect CITX 220093 and remediate any ground spillage. Inspection of CITX 220093 revealed that the sample (line) port valve was not closed and its closure plug was not applied. This valve was closed and the closure plug applied and tool tightened, ending any further product release. Non-evaporated spillage on the tank shell was wiped. Recovered free product atop the ground was placed into 55 gallon recovery drums and absorbent padding was placed over the ground spill area to soak up additional product. Afterwards, impacted soils were excavated and earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On August 25, 2008 at 13:00 at the CSXT Frontier Yard, Engineering Track personnel reported that GATX 21423 (load Sulfuric Acid UN1830) had released product from the top of the tank car. The engineering employees evacuated the area. A CSX HazMat Sentinel discovered GATX 21423 to have product on the top and sides of the car and approximately 1 to 2 gallons on the ground, and it appeared that the Rupture Disc and its assembly was the release point. The car was isolated and the shipper, Olin Corp, from Niagara Falls, NY, NYS-DEC and a CSXT HazMat Manager were notified. EP+S of Vermont and SPSI, CSXT response contractors, where dispatched to the scene. The CSXT hazmat manager found that the rupture disc had actuated and that the retainer for the disc assembly had been unseated from the rupture disc housing. Of the 18 CSX engineering personnel in the area of the release, 13 employees were medically checked with the assistance of Erie County HazMat, Rural Metro Ambulance, Rescue Hose Fire Company, the City of Buffalo Fire Dept and HazMat Operations Team and CTEH for possible exposure to Sulfuric Acid. Contractor personnel EP+S of VT decontaminated the area where GATX 21423 had released product and decontaminated the equipment for any residue of possible product. SPSI changed out the complete rupture disc housing assembly, decontaminated the car and qualified the tank car repairs. GATX 21423 was released on August 28, 2008 for transport.  Cause Code: 441  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+2) = 200
column169: No additional comments.

column168: AIRGAS VEHICLE WAS TRAVELLING NORTHBOUND ON KS HWY 61 FROM HUTCHINSON, KS (ORIGIN) TO SAUNA, KS (DESTINATION). HIGHWAY 61 IS A TWO LANE ASPHALT HIGHWAY. AIRGAS DRIVER STATES HE HAD JUST APPROACHED A STOP LIGHT AT 3O” STREET IN HUTCHINSON AND HAD SLOWED DOWN TO APPROXIMATELY 35 MPH AND THEN PROCEEDED THROUGH THE LIGHT. DRIVER STATES HE HAD TAKEN OFF HIS GLASSES TO SCRATCH HIS EYES BECAUSE OF ALLERGIES AND FORGOT TO PUT THEM BACK ON. DRIVER STATES AS HE APPROACHED A CURVE IN THE HIGHWAY, WHAT HE BELIEVES TO BE A COYOTE JUMPED IN FRONT OF HIS VEHICLE. DRIVER STATES HE TRIED TO AVOID HITTING THE ANIMAL BY SWERVING TOWARD THE NORTHBOUND LANE SHOULDER. THIS CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO PARTIALLY LEAVE THE HIGHWAY ON THE RIGHT SIDE AND THE TRAILER BEGAN WHIPPING FROM SIDE TO SIDE. AS HE ATTEMPTED TO RETURN THE VEHICLE TO THE HIGHWAY, THE DRIVER THEN OVERCORRECTED THE VEHICLE, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO SWERVE INTO THE ONCOMING SOUTHBOUND LANE. WHILE ATTEMPTING TO RETURN THE VEHICLE TO THE NORTHBOUND LANE, THE DRIVER OVERCORRECTED AGAIN, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO PARTIALLY LEAVE THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY AGAIN. AS THE DRIVER TRIED TO RETURN THE VEHICLE TO THE NORTHBOUND LANE, BOTH TRACTOR AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER ONTO PASSENGER SIDE. DRIVER STATES HE DID NOT APPLY BRAKES FOR FEAR OFJACKKNIFMG THE TRACTOR/TRAILER. THE AIRGAS VEHICLE (SEMI-TRAILER) WAS LOADED WITH COMPRESSED GAS CYLINDERS WHICH WERE SECURED TO STEEL CYLINDER PALLETS VIA SECUREMENT STRAPS. DUE TO ROLLOVER, MANY CYLINDERS WERE THROWN OUT AND AWAY FROM THE PALLET TRAILER, INCLUDING THE CYLINDER DISCUSSED IN SECTION III. THE VALVE, A CGA-580 VALVE MANUFACTURED BY SHERWOOD, WAS SHEARED OFF OF A 300 CUBIC FT. CAPACITY DOT-3AA HIGH PRESSURE CYLINDER. IT IS UNKNOWN WHAT OBJECT CAUSED THE MANIFOLD TO SHEAR. ESTIMATED RELEASE DURATION IS 30— 60 SECONDS. THIS VEHICLE WAS ALSO CARRYING SEVEN (7) DOT-4L CYLINDERS WHICH WERE INITIALLY THOUGHT TO BE COMPROMISED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT. WHEN THE INITIAL TELEPHONIC REPORT WAS MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, IT WAS REPORTED THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE CYLINDERS WERE LOST DUE TO SOME SORT OF PACKAGING FAILURE. IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED THAT THE CONTENTS OF THESE SEVEN CYLINDERS WERE NOT LOST DUE TO EQUIPMENT FAILURE, BUT RATHER TO NORMAL VENTINg

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering fuel to a customer location. Prior to unloading the Plant Manager, Lawrence McDaly, signed off on the product integrity sheet, accepting the 7500 gallons of ULSD they had ordered. The driver began to unload product. The driver was able to pump close to 7200 gallons of ULSD when he noticed fuel leaking from the vent closure. Driver immediately stopped the flow of product but approximately 15 gallons leaked onto the concrete containment area. No product reached soil or drains. The spill was cleaned up by the customer by in house personnel. The spill was cause by an excessive amount scheduled for fuel delivery.
column169: The spill was caused by an error on part of the customer, too much fuel was ordered. The customer was given information on proper ordering of fuel and how to avoid this in the future. The excess fuel not delivered was brought to another client location.

column168: RTMX 3174 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) at the repair track queue for side bearing issues, was reported emanating a product odor. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected RTMX 3174 finding liquid product on its side shell. The source of this liquid release was traced back to the threaded liquid valve connection which was two turns less than tool tight. The responder tool tightened the valve body and the liquid leak ebbed. The responder then depressurized the inner tank using the vapor valve. After RTMX 3174 was depressurized, the responder removed the liquid valve and applied Teflon tape to its threads. The liquid valve was then reapplied and tool tightened which ended any further liquid leakage. All spillage that didn't evaporate was wiped. Honeywell seal numbered 0073203 was removed and BNSF seal numbered 06157905 was applied in its place.  The side specification stencil on RTMX 3174 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2004 and next due in 2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Univar driver picked up two IBC's of waste Trichlorethylene from generator.  When driver arrived at next pickup, noticed a small leak from one of the IBC's. column169: Further training by tote vendor regarding proper inspection of IBC's.  Installation of gaskets and all fittings should be inspected and verified correct before tote is sent for use.

column168: A BNSF switchman reported product odor emanating from TILX 302052 (DOT 112J340W tank car) in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected TILX 302052 and reported no product odor was readily detectable as they approached this tank car. Responders found all valves secure. Additional 'bubble testing' revealed a small vapor leak at one area of the pressure plate. TILX 302052 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting further evaluation and cessation of this pressure plate leak. Contract responders arrived and inspected the pressure plate securement of TILX 302052. The responders reported two pressure plate securement nuts on the mounting studs to be less than tool tight. The responders proceeded to retighten all the pressure plate stud nuts in the recommended sequential order. After this was accomplished, no further product odor or vapor release from the pressure plate area was detectable.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Pallet of four 55 gallon drums was shrink-wrapped to unitize pallet. The pallet was centered in the nose of the trailer. There was no dunnage on either side of the pallet. During the transportation phase, the drums shifted sideways, with one drum impacting the side of the pallet. This caused a puncture in the sidewall of the drum and allowed 40 gallons of product to leak out of the drum into the trailer and subsequently into the rest area.    An environmental contractor was dispatched to neutralize the release material and clean up the impacted areas.

On 8/27/08 at 1:50pm a loader was in the process of loading an ethanol trailer when three bolts on the four-bolt flange of ethanol pump PM 9990 broke. The pump was immediately shut down and we estimate that 2 gallons of ethanol was spilled onto the asphalt surface. All material was cleaned up and disposed of in a proper container. The pump was repaired and put back in service.
column169: The broken bolts were removed and the pump was repaired. RBT was called and they are in the process of changing these bolts from stainless steel to Grade 8 bolts with new lock washers. This change was implemented across our system to prevent the same event from occurring again.

column168: On August 28th at 10:33, personnel in the CSXT Georgetown Yard discovered GATX56374, a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid, N.O.S., releasing odor and leaking product from top of car.  The car was isolated and Chemtrec (report number 2008082800166) assisted in contacting the shipper, Citgo Lube + Wax. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway nozzle gasket missing which caused the release of product.  In addition, all four placards were missing from the railcar.  Hepaco representatives applied the required placards and installed a 20" manway nozzle gasket.  The car was then released to destination.  Approximately 1 gallon was released from the container. This incident did not require a special switching move.     Cause Code: 207  NARRI = 5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Driver had stopped at our facility to take a break.  While there, he noticed a drip coming from the bottom of the bonnet that connects to the discharge valve on the cargo tank.  He put a bucket under it to see if it might be rain water that was in the insulation.  By morning the drip hadn't stopped so to err on the side of safety, the product was successfully transferred to another cargo tank.  We had an emergency response crew stand by during the transfer in case of any problems.  The trailer was washed and taken to the shop to be inspected.
column169: The sump on the cargo tank had a crack and some pits.  It was welded to prevent anymore incidents.

column168: Driver was by cargo tank controls using air pressure to unload into totes.  Plant employee was handling the drumming nozzle.  About a quarter of the way into the unload, a pinhole leak developed between the external and bleeder valve on the cargo tank.  Product sprayed out when the plant employee closed the nozzle and the pressure built up.  The unload was terminated until the problem could be fixed.
column169: The trailer was taken into the shop for repairs.  A crack was found on the nipple of the external valve.  It was welded to prevent further problems.  The load was successfully delivered.

column168: RTMX 12136 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) rolled out from a yard track onto a switch lead track derailing on its side after encountering a split-point derail. The cause of the roll-out was attributed to a defective hand brake on RTMX 12136. RTMX 12136 released product from the vapor valve that was damaged and sheared off during the derailment. During the derailment, the safety railing collapsed into the unpinned valve protective housing cover which bent the housing cover upward and into the body of the vapor valve. Product release ended when RTMX 12136 was up-righted at 0930 hrs. MDT, 8/28/08. The spilled product on the ground was mixed with aggregate and was used as paving material atop a nearby roadway in the railyard. The derailment damage to RTMX 12136 necessitated product transfer. The remaining product in RTMX 12136 was heated and transferred into another suitable tank car on 9/17/08 without further incident. Afterwards, RTMX 12136 was cleaned and purged.   The side specification stencil indicated that RTMX 12136's tank qualification was completed in the year 2007 and next due in 2017.

column168: Terminal 198 UE driver, Harold Rose was transferring the tote in question from his RPM van to the HVXP dock. It was discovered that there was a leak coming from the bottom of the tote. After visual inspection by Mr. Rose and SWB/184 Operations Supervisor, Bruce Sweda, it was determined that a piece   of the outer metal wire container punctured the plastic tote on the bottom just behind the valve. The reported cause is that the metal cage around the plastic tote was rusted in locations. The bottom corner of the plastic tote that became punctured was from a portion of the metal cage that had sever  e rust, the metal was broke and pointed and punctured the plastic tote. ABF employees on location identified the cause of the puncture to be due to the rust as well the contracted clean up team. It was mentioned that the tote should have never been offered for transportation by the shipper nor accep  ted by ABF for transportation.~NOTE: this is a non-spec IBC. This is the reason the package identification markings are not documented on this report.

column168: Driver was using pump to transfer product from the cargo tank to customer storage tank.  Customer rep said there was plenty of room in the storage tank for all of the product.  Tank was 250 feet away from the cargo tank and rep said he would watch it.  The tank overflowed and there was still 20 gallons left in the cargo tank.  Spilled product went into the containment area around the tank.
column169: A sight glass on the tank would have helped.  The only way to measure how much was in the tank was by sticking it.

column168: After the cargo tank was loaded at the shipper, a drip was noticed coming from the skin of the cargo tank on each side of the internal valve.  A bucket was put under the drip and the product was successfully transferred to a different trailer.
column169: the trailer was cleaned and inspected.  It was found to have a small crack in the sump area. The trailer is still in the shop awaiting repair.

column168: A BNSF train operating on the Stillwater Central RR derailed 13 rail cars including 8 tank cars ladened with petroleum crude oil. Five of these derailed tank cars were compromised and involved in a product fire from the derailment. The cause of the derailment was attributed to the cross level of the track irregular, not at joints. The derailment occurred NE of the town of Luther, OK and authorities initially ordered a precautionary evacuation of residents within 1/2 mile of the derailment site. Later, the evacuation was expanded to one mile and three miles downwind. The evacuation impacted approximately 14 homes (approx. 35 people). All fires were extinguished around 2000 hrs. CDT, 8/22/08 and the evacuation was lifted. Air quality and soil monitoring were initiated and continued throughout this incident.  (Tank Car #1) TILX 193325 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side and incurred a side shell split toward the top of the shell towards the A-end. A product fire ensued from the compromised shell, the manway area between the nozzle and the manway cover and at the liquid valve. The fire was extinguished and the remaining product inside TILX 193325 was transferred into portable frac tanks after the tank car cooled off. Pooled product mixed with water and other liquids on the ground was vacuumed into portable frac tanks and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  (Tank Car #2) UTLX 207514 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side. A product fire ensued from the liquid valve and vapor valve orifices after these valves were sheared off in the derailment. The fire melted the manway gasket and leaking product ignited, adding to the product fire. The fire was extinguished and the remaining product inside UTLX 207514 was transferred into portable frac tanks after the tank car cooled off. Pooled product mixed with water and other liquids on the ground was vacuumed into portable frac tanks and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  (Tank Car #3)TILX 191938 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side. A product fire ensued around the liquid valve and the manway cover area. The fire was extinguished and the remaining product inside TILX 191938 was transferred into portable frac tanks after the tank car cooled off. Pooled product mixed with water and other liquids on the ground was vacuumed into portable frac tanks and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  (Tank Car #4)UTLX 201925 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side and all product within was deemed consumed from a fire that ensued from a pressure/heat induced tear in the side shell near the B-end. The fire was extinguished towards the end of the product burn off.  (Tank Car #5)TILX 194831 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed leaning and lost product in the fire that ensued from a pressure/heat induced tear near the top side shell towards the B-end. The fire was extinguished and the remaining product inside TILX 194831 was transferred into portable frac tanks after the tank car had cooled down.  P
column169: No additional comments.

The derailment occurred NE of the town of Luther, OK and authorities initially ordered a precautionary evacuation of residents within 1/2 mile of the derailment site. Later, the evacuation was expanded to one mile and three miles downwind. The evacuation impacted approximately 14 homes (approx. 35 people). All fires were extinguished around 2000 hrs. CDT, 8/22/08 and the evacuation was lifted. Air quality and soil monitoring were initiated and continued throughout this incident.  (Tank Car #1) TILX 193325 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side and incurred a side shell split toward the top of the shell towards the A-end. A product fire ensued from the compromised shell, the manway area between the nozzle and the manway cover and at the liquid valve. The fire was extinguished and the remaining product inside TILX 193325 was transferred into portable frac tanks after the tank car cooled off. Pooled product mixed with water and other liquids on the ground was vacuumed into portable frac tanks and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  (Tank Car #2) UTLX 207514 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side. A product fire ensued from the liquid valve and vapor valve orifices after these valves were sheared off in the derailment. The fire melted the manway gasket and leaking product ignited, adding to the product fire. The fire was extinguished and the remaining product inside UTLX 207514 was transferred into portable frac tanks after the tank car cooled off. Pooled product mixed with water and other liquids on the ground was vacuumed into portable frac tanks and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  (Tank Car #3)TILX 191938 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side. A product fire ensued around the liquid valve and the manway cover area. The fire was extinguished and the remaining product inside TILX 191938 was transferred into portable frac tanks after the tank car cooled off. Pooled product mixed with water and other liquids on the ground was vacuumed into portable frac tanks and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  (Tank Car #4)UTLX 201925 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed on its side and all product within was deemed consumed from a fire that ensued from a pressure/heat induced tear in the side shell near the B-end. The fire was extinguished towards the end of the product burn off.  (Tank Car #5)TILX 194831 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed leaning and lost product in the fire that ensued from a pressure/heat induced tear near the top side shell towards the B-end. The fire was extinguished and the remaining product inside TILX 194831 was transferred into portable frac tanks after the tank car had cooled down.  P

column168: Subject of the leak was a single 5 gallon pail, that was loaded on the rear of a 52 ft van tractor combination.  THE PAIL WAS LOADED BY A CONWAY EMPLOYEE IN THE middle of the trailer sitting between two palletized shippments. No dunnage or restrictive measures was used BY THE EMPLYEE TO KEEP THE PAIL STABLE IN TRANSIT.  THE pallets shifted in transit allowing the pail to fall over and become crushed by the moving pallets. The pail cracked DUE TO THE CRUSHING AND STARTED TO LEAK.  WHEN THE  trailer was opened at the Dock in Butte Mt. by a Conway employee an odor was noticed and the overturned Pail was seen by the employee.  The employee notified larry McGillvray the supervisor on shift ( myself) at which time I removed all employees from the immediate area until the leaking material could be identified.  There was no  equipment being used at the time of discovery. I retrieved the appropriate coso to identify the leaking product  and called Conway safety dept and Chemtrec emergency hot line to get instruction on emergency precautions and proper clean up and disposistion instructions.  Upon receiving instructions the spill was neutralized and cleaned up, putting the leaking pail and all contaminated clean up materials in an Over Pack container in the OS&D HAZARDOUS AREA AT THE BUTTE DOCK waitig for disposistion instruction from the Shipper
column169: Conway has proper loading instructions in place for hazardous shipments if followed would have eliminated this spill. The emplyee must be retrained on the proper loading of hazardous shipments.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON IL, RT 45 WHEN HE HIT A MULE THAT GOT OUT OF IT'S PEN, STANDING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROAD, THE HOOD ON THE TRUCK CAME UP, CAUSING OUR DRIVER TO LOOSE CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE, AND ROLLED OVER & SLIDING DOWN THE HIGHWAY LAYING ON IT'S SIDE. FUEL WAS DRIPPING OUT OF THE FRONT COMPARTMENT OF THE TANK CAR, A SECOND TRUCK TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND CAME UPON THE SCENE NOT SEEING OUR TRUCK LAYING ON IT'S SIDE, HIT THE BACK COMPARMENT WHICH GREATLY INCREASED THE AMOUNT SPILLAGE. FIRE DEPTS. EMT. AND A CLEAN-UP  CONTRACTOR WERE NOTIFIED, WE CONTAINED THE SPILL, UNTILL EPA OFFICIALS ARRIVED ON SITE TO ASSIST. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS ESTIMATED AT 1 HR. WE USED CONTAAINMENT SOCKS, A PUMPER TRUCK, AND A BACKHOE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THE FUEL LEFT ON THE TANKER WAS PUMPED OUT A TAKEN TO A BULK SITE. 18" OF SOIL WAS  TAKEN OUT AND SOIL LORCS WERE TAKEN BY EPA, AT THIS TIME WE ARE WAITING FOR THE RESULTS BACK FOR EPA, SO WE CAN FINISH CLEANING  UP THE SPILL, AND RETURN IT TO THE ORGINAL FORM.

column168: UTLX 669355 was switched over the hump at UPRRs North Platte Yard and experienced an overspeed through the master and group retarders, exited the east end of the bowl and collided with locomotive UPY 822.      Investigation of the car revealed two of eight manway swing bolts in the down position and one more swing bolt in position but not hand tight.  On inspection, the manway gasket was also found to be deformed and in poor condition.  The gasket was replaced and the manway resecured.      Product was also found to have been released from the pressure relief valve in a spray pattern.  Its believed that this release occurred when the tank car collided with the locomotive due to the sudden hydraulic surge inside the tank.
column169: Shipper needs to insure that manway gaskets are in proper condition for use and that hinged and bolted manway covers are properly secured with all manway swing bolts in positioned and tight.

Employee was at customer location filling forklift cylinders with the bobtail hose.  The bobtail hose was hooked up to a cylinder. The bobtail hose nozzle would not shut off or close and the Employee could not stop the release of propane.  Employee shut down the truck to prevent any more propane from getting into the bobtail hose.   The Fire Department was called. The customer was notified- but resumed business because there was so much space between the leak site and the buildings/employees.    The only propane which released was contained within the bobtail hose and the cylinder which was 8-10 gallons.  The Fire Department transported the cylinder and the hose to an open area to let the propane release.
column169: The hose nozzle was defective.  The truck was taken back at the Service Unit and a new nozzle replaced the faulty one before the truck was used again for any deliveries.  The hose nozzle was sent back to the manufacturer to be inspected.

TERRY NOTICED THAT THERE WAS LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE BACK OF HIS TRAILER.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID WAS THATOF, UN1210, PRINTING INK, 3,PG II.  TERRY CALLED HISDISPATCH WHO THEN CONTACTED WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS (405-549-8487) TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  WCEC (WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS)CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL AT THE ORIGINAL DISCOVERY SITE WHICH WAS AT THE TWON PUMP IN MILLTOW MT.WCEC WAS NOT ABELT TO CLEAN THE SPILL IN TRAILER ON ENTERPRISR WAY STE B, MISSOULA, MT 59808. WCEC FOLLOWED THE TRAILER TO THE CON-WAY FREIGHT DOCK TO FINISH THE CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL.  WITH THE HELP OF THE LOCAL CON-WAY FREIGHT SCM AND FOS (KEVIN TULLY AND CHRIS WILLIAMS), THE SPILL WAS LOCATED ABOUT EIGHT FEET IN FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER ON THE RIGHT HAND SIDE.  THE SPILL BELONGED TO WAYBILL 236-614243.  THIS WAYBILL WAS FOR ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF UN1210, PRINTING INK,3, PGII.  UPON REACHING THE DRUM IN THE TRAILER, APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF LIQUID HAD SPILLED FROM THE DRUM.  THE LEAKING WAS ISOLATED TO THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM ONLY.  WHEN THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND PUT IN A OVER PACK DRUM,WE COULD SEE THAT THE SEAM AT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM HAD FAILED.  THE SPLIT IN THE SEAM IS APPROXIMATELY 4" LONG AND LESS THAN ONE MILLIMETER IN WIDTH.  THIS RESULTED IN A SLOW RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  IT APPEARS THAT THE PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FOR SEVERAL DAYS.  THE LOAD WAS DISPATCHED OUT OF MINNEAPOLIS, MN ON AUGUST 8TH, 2008 AT 1152AM.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON INDUSTRIAL PARKWAY (HIWAY 611) AT APROX 35 MPH. AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF OLD MOBILE HWY, A CAR THAT HAS BEEN EAST BOUND ON OLD MOBILE HWY MOVE A LEFT TURN IN FRONT OF HIM. OUR DRIVER BRAKED AND SLOWDOWN HIS AIR HORN. THE CAR PULLED BACKING  THE OTHER CARS & OUR DRIVER THOUGH HE WAS OK TO PROCEED AND TURN THE CAR STARTED TO CHANGE BACK INTO OUR DRIVERS CARS VERY FAST. OUR DRIVER BRAKED AND STOPPED TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID STRIKING THE CAR. AS HE DID SO, THE RIGHT SIDE TIRES DROPPPED OFF THE PAVEMENT & THIS CAUSED OUR TRUCK TO ROLL OVER. THERE IS NOT A SHOULDER ON THIS ROADWAY. ONCE THE PAVEMENT ENDS THERE IS AN APPROX  TWO FOOT DROP OFF INTO THE DIRT/GRASS. THIS DROP OFF CAUSED THE ROLLOVER. THERE IS NO GUARD RAIL VERY MINOR LEAKING FROM TANKERS TOP GASGET WHICH WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP SAME DAY AS EVENT. LEAKED ESTMATED AT NO MORE THAN TWO GALLONS. BUT WAS MJS LIKLY LESS THAN THAT.
column169: THERE IS A SLIGHT CURVE IN ROADWAY CURVE N OLD MOBILE HWY CHICH MAY LIMIT VISABILITY TO VEHICCLES TRAVELING EAST ON OLD MOBILE HWY. INDUSTRIAL PARKWAY HAS THE RIGHT OF WAY. . THESE ROADS ARE IN A LARGE INDUSTRIAL PARK AREA. THE CHEVRON COMPANY AND OTHER CHEMICAL PLANTS ARE ON THIS ROAD. INUSTRIL PARKWAY HAS NO PROPER SHOULDER. THE PAVEMENT ENDS AND THERE IS DIR WITH HIGH GRASSES. THERE ARE ALOT OF AREAS WHERE THERE ARE CANNOT DROP OFF FFROM PAVEMENT TO DIRT. THERE SHOULD BE SHOULDERS ON THIS ROAD AND A TRAFFIC LIGHT AT THIS INTERSECTION.

column169: Material handlers need to pay attention to their clearances and use dunnage when loading and handling these types of containers and commodities.

column169: This could have been prevented if this shipment had been properly blocked and braced.This incident was reviewed with the outbound staffed from origin facility to prevent future occurrences.

Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material, the lid and closure were put back on the drum and tighted, and the drum shipped to ultimate consignee without further incident.
column169: Shiiper's need to insure that lids and closures are on the container properly and tighten to specific torque recommendations.

column169: SHPR NEEDS A MORE THOROUGH INSPECTION PROCESS BEFORE DRUMS ARE FILLED. MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFOR IT LEAVES ORIGIN! DRUMS, PAILS AND BAGS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF! RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DEFECTIVE DRUMS AND OTHER PACKAGING CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ,CHEMICALS OR LIQUIDS SHOULD NOT BE PICKED UP AND TRANSFERRED.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. REMOVE AND AVOID OBSTRUCTIONS IN LANE OF TRAVEL TO PREVENT DAMAGE AND UNSAFE SITUATIONS. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT.WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column169: ISSUED OF WARNING LETTER AND APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE, WITH REVIEWS AND INSTRUCTIONS ON SAFE PROCEDURES REGARDING PROPER UNLOADING, LOADING AND HANDLING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND FREIGHT. RETRAINING SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUID OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NO EASILY DAMAGED. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ONTOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.
