column168: Mr. Baker stated that a Gasoline tanker owned by Potter Oil had rolled over. Mr. Baker stated that there were 2 compartments that were punctured and releasing fuel. Mr. Baker estimated 8600 gallons of fuel on the tanker it’s self. Mr. Baker stated that the two compartments contain approximately 900 gallons each. Mr. Baker stated that the valves were accessible. Mr. Baker wanted Environmental Management to respond to the incident.   Team arrived onsite and investigated the incident it was determined that the tanker had to be hot taped. The team hot taped the tanker and began recovering the fuel. Potter Oil was utilized to recover the fuel. Approximately 6600 Gallons of Fuel was recovered. It was estimated that 1300 - 2000 gallons was released into the soil. On 8-26-08 thru 9-5-08 the team excavated 654.56 tons of contaminated soil and recovered 660 gallons of water and fuel. It was estimated that 100 gallons of fuel was recovered from the excavated trench. The team backfield the excavation and is pending sod. The 656.56 tons of contaminated soil was disposed of at the Red Carpet Landfill in Meno, OK. The state is requiring monitoring wells based on the fact that the fuel reached the ground water. Access agreements are also pending

column168: A HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED TO BE STAINED DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT THE VEOLIA 10-DAY INTRANSIT FACILITY LOCATED IN PHILADELPHIA, PA.  UPON REVIEWING THE ASSOCIATED SHIPPING PAPERS, IT WAS DETERMINED THE CONTAINER CONTAINED ORGANIC ACIDS THAT WERE IN LAB PACK QUANTITIES (PINT - QUART SIZED BOTTLES) OF VARIOUS ORGANIC ACIDS.  THE PACKING MATERIAL (VERMICULITE) HAD ABSORBED THE LIQUID FROM THE BROKEN BOTTLE INSIDE THE POLY LINED CONTAINER, BUT THE INSIDE POLY LINER HAD A HOLE WHICH ALLOWED THE LIQUID TO PERMEATE THE OUTER FIBER BOX. THERE WAS NO RELEASE FROM THE CONTAINER TO THE TRAILER FLOOR, ONLY TO THE BOX AND VERMICULITE INSIDE THE BOX. THE SOILED CONTAINER ALONG WITH ALL CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE OVERPACKED INTO A NEW CONTAINER FOR SHIPMENT TO THE APPROVED DISPOSAL LOCATION.
column169: THE VEOLIA EMPLOYEES WHO INITIALLY PACKED THE CONTAINER PERFORMED THE TASK CORRECTLY. THE CONTAINER WAS PROPERLY LINED WITH A POLY LINER AND THERE WAS SUFFICIENT ABSORBANT PACKING MATERIAL INCLUDED BETWEEN THE BOTTLES TO CUSHION THE BOTTLES DURING TRANSPORT. THE CAUSE FOR THE BROKEN BOTTLE IS UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME. IT APPEARS THAT THE INSIDE POLY LINER WAS SLICED WHEN THE BOX OF LINERS WAS OPENED WITH A UTILITY KNIFE. THE HOLE WAS NOT SEEN BY THE EMPLOYEES WHO PACKED THE CONTAINER. THE EMPLOYEES WERE TRAINED TO INSPECT ALL PARTS OF THE PACKAGE BEFORE FILLING WITH WASTE MATERIALS FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: August 29, 2008: At approximately 2:00AM, Conrail yard crews reported an odor of gas in the yard.  Further inspection by Conrail's A. Richter, Mgr. Risk Mgmt., and REACT Env. Services' R. Gould, found odor originating from tank car PLMX 139007, residue last contained Liquefied Petroleum Gas.  Soap solution applied to all valves/fittings inside protective housing, finding two (2) liquid valves not completely closed, and closure plugs for same were not tool tight.      Both valves made secure and okayed for shipment to original destination.
column169: During same inspection, four (4) other tank cars, coupled to PLMX 139007, in the same service, were inspected.  GATX 74983, containing residue of Liquefied Petroleum Gas (same shipper/consignee) found with the sample valve closure plug less than tool tight.  Plug secured during inspection and car okayed to original destination.

column168: On 8/6/08 around 02:00, our security guard was contacted by the railroad crew that while spotting cars onour property, there was a strong odor coming from around car TILX200212. The guard notified the control room and operator Ronnie Moore went to investigate. He noticed a small amount of liquid seeping from under one of the dome covers. The control room notified Monica McLaughlin (supervisor on call). It was determined that the liquid had spilled during the spotting of the car as there was no more liquid comingf rom the dome area. I was notified of this when I arrived around 06:00.1 along with Jon Elliott went to investigate. I removed the seal from the dome and found the four bolts on the bottom flange of the unloading valve to be loose. We tightened the bolts and cleaned the area of any Acrylic Acid. (Statement provided by Mark Freeman, CA Operations Supervisor) Please find picture attached.
column169: The shipper of this railcar along with other raw material providers have been notified. There have been numerous meetings and e-mails exchanged to prevent similar future occurrences. The railroad has been in continuous contact with NAN and has been advised to report any future railcar problems and/or potential problems.

column168: Brian Morgan, Citizen, reported smoke or vapor coming from a white tankcar which was travelling west toward Alpine, TX. The train, identified as the QEWWC 29 , was notified to stop for inspection. The Alpine, Texas Fire dept. was notified and responded. The Brewster County Emergency Management Coordinator initiated evacuation in the area of the tankcar. Mr. John Jackson, Manager Hazardous Materials was notified and a conference call was established with the Alpine Fire Dept. Further inspection of the train by the Fire Dept. revealed three tankcar were releasing product.lt was determined the tankcars contained Argon and all three cars were leaking from inside the control boxes. The IAPX 1026 and the IAPX1030 were determined to be releasing product from the liquid fill/withdrawal valves. The BOCX 3017 was leaking from a fitting on a feeder line to a pressure gage.The Alpine Fire Dept. defrosted the control boxes and closed the open valves, stopping the release. Mr. Jackson responded with VivaEnvironmental Contractor .inspected .repaired and secured the cars for transportation.
column169: Shipper should review loading / unloading procedures and training.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A 55 GALLON DRUM OF LIQUID FELL OVER DUE TO IT NOT BEING PROPERLY BLOCKED, BRACED AND SECURED.  THE DRUM AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  REMOVE AND AVOID OBSTRUCTIONS IN LANE OF TRAVEL TO PREVENT DAMAGE AND UNSAFE SITUATIONS.  PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER ANDSAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOPI USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: While fueling a yacht at Berth 98 in the APM Terminal, the fuel truck driver noticed a Gantry crane moving toward the tanker truck.. Despite the yelling of the driver and others in the area, the crane kept moving. The crane struck the passenger side front compartment and punctured the tank shell. Fuel began spilling out onto the pier and into the bay. Emergency Services were called and the driver began pumping fuel from the punctured into an empty on the truck..  APM Response crews began containing the fuel and cleaning up as much as they could. Miller Environmental responded and boomed the bay and did pier cleanup. Cleanup began and was completed by APM and Miller Environmental.
column169: The incident was reviewed by APM’s safety personnel and are currently making changes to prevent further accidents.

column168: FJ Driver was traveling on a 2 lane freeway when a dark SUV cut over into him. FJ swerved to miss the SUV and hit directly into the guardrail on the passenger side of FJ's truck.  FJ's trailer also came in contact with the guardrail rupturing loading heads on the DOT 406 tanker.  An estimated 20 gallons were spilled from the load lines.  A hazmat team was called out for the remediation and cleanup which was completed the same night.  No injuries to FJ's driver and the other party drove off witout stopping.
column169: We counseled with the driver about defensive driving techniques which we continually are teaching through our Smith System training and various other monthly safety training meetings.  Our driver made the decision of either hitting the SUV or hitting the guardrail.

column168: Tractor/Trailer was stopped due to odor detected from the trailer and a leaking load.  Load was taken to a Recovery facility to further evaluate the status.  A 1/8 inch hole was evident, in the side of a drum, approx one inch from the bottom of the drum.  A makeshift patch was observed adjacent tothe leaking drum on the floor of the trailer.  Oil dry was applied to the area impacted by the leaking dum and the leaking drum was over-packed, placed back on the trailer to be transported to the TSD facility.  A copy of an Incident Notification Investigation form, drafted by Clean Harbors personnel was later obtained.  It stated that while loading the trailer the drum fell off a pallet.  Clean Harbors personnel load our trailers.  When we arrive at the site we pick up the pre-loaded trailer the driver inspects the load for any visual leaks/odors and proceeds with the load to the final destination.  At no point was our driver aware or notified of a damaged drum when arriving at the pick up location.
column169: It is the policy of ETGI that training for all drivers be held on a quarterly basis.  This includes Spill Control, Contingency Implementation and Response to emergencies.  All drivers are required to take the following steps when accepting loads: Review all paperowrk, do a visual inspection of the load, check for load security.

column168: On 8/29/2005 Said driver Dennis Etherton fueled at the Conoco Phillips loading station at Medford, Oklahoma.  Said driver after loading his trailer w/9377 gallons of Propane (UN1978).  Said driver after orientation at the loading facility drove his tractor/trailer onto Hwy 81 and approached the nearby Rail Road Crossing. Said driver failed to stop and pulled his truck on to the tracks.  Said driver failed to see the on coming freight train. (There are no warning lights or arms at the track).  The on coming train collided with the truck loaded with propane.  The crash caused the truck tank to explode releasing the propane in a large ball of fire and sent parts of the truck up to 2700+ feet from the scene. The trailer separated from the truck causing the trailer to swing around and up against the train engine causing the engineer and brakeman on the engine to loose their life.  Said truck driver was wearing his seat belt and was trapped in the burning truck.  The tanks on the truck had approximately   200 gallons of diesel fuel which burned and probably caused the death of the driver. He was extracted and sent to the Medford Hospital and later died at burn center located in Wichita, Kansas on Monday September 1st.    Nine police,Sheriff, 1st responders,ambulance and Vance Air Force Base responded to the fire and explosion.  There were no casualties during the fighting of the fire.  Electricity was knocked out in the town of Medford, Oklahoma for approximately 6 hours.  This account is to the best of our knowledge at this time.  The responders have not completed their reports at this time neither has the investigating agency The Olhahoma Highway Patrol Located in Oklahoma City< Oklahoma.
column169: Our company has hired an expert in transportation safety full time to oversee safety operations, train drivers and test them when necessary.  Said Safety director or a trained driver will give each driver hired a road test which includes crossing   railroads then he will give the driver a written test that will be placed in the training book for review. Our company will take due care in hiring only the best of CDL drivers and will continue to follow the FMCSR's when hiring all drivers.  The hiring process is located in the driver handbook and in the company DOT regulations book.  The following company regulation concerning Rail Road crossing is as follows.    RAILROAD CROSSING REGULATIONS FOR ANDERSON GAS & PROPANE DRIVERS:(MANDATORY TRAINING)    According to the FMCSR's all Hazardous Material transport vehicles must come to a complete stop before proceding across the Rail Road Crossing.  Hazardous Material vehicles must not stop no closer than 15 feet and no further back than 50ft from the track crossing and will follow the following steps.    1.   Drivers will call dispatch when they are leaving  the loading facility.  2.   Drivers will turn off all radio's in the truck.  3.   Drivers will turn off all other noise making devices.  4.   Drivers will roll down both the drivers side and passenger side windows for        train signals, crossing signals and horns from possible other devises.  5.   Drivers will select the proper gear prior to crossing tracks.  6.   Drivers will not shift while crossing said Rail Road tracks  7.   Drivers will turn on their 4way signals prior to crossing tracks    Drivers who are cited by a law enforcement officer for illegal crossing track or observed by a company official will be terminated.
